This paper discusses the measurement of scholarly impact using citation data, which is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. The focus on Google Scholar citation counts suggests a focus on digital libraries (cs.DL) and information retrieval (cs.IR). The use of citation data to identify empirical patterns could also be relevant to database systems (cs.DB) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI), as well as machine learning (cs.LG) which often involves analyzing large datasets.
